        <sec>
            <title>Challenges for the realisation of a mobility dream</title>
            <p>The ultimate target in any deployment of automated vehicles in public transportation is to create a sustainable, economically viable and commercially realistic deployment of citizen- and user-centric public transportation service. This should be based on proven business models and concepts, like valorisation and preservation of past investments, promotion of competition between technology providers, suppression of customer lock-in situations, and development of cross-section business models and partnerships for the creation of viable, sustainable and optimized business ecosystems.</p>
            <p>From an economic perspective, the use of AVs cannot be made profitable today due to the elevated costs linked to the deployment of AVs in an urban environment. Although the major visible costs today in full scale deployment of AVs are the costs of the on-board safety operator (due to the small capacity of AVs the cost ratio per passenger is too high), other very important costs are not yet being considered by the operators due to the fact that all of today&#x2019;s deployments are small scale and of very short durations, being &#x201c;simple&#x201d; proves of concepts.</p>
            <p>In our work in the AVENUE project we identified eight major issues that are not yet fully understood by the PTOs and have a major impact in any large-scale deployment of AVs in public transportation.</p>
            <sec>
                <title>Life time of Automated vehicles</title>
                <p> It is expected that in a large-scale deployment the PTO will deploy hundreds of AVs in the city, this being one of its major capital investments. However, AVs are based on IT systems which are evolving and will continue to evolve relatively fast for the next decades. With the evolution of the technology, it is to be expected that the regulatory requirements will also be adapted in order to consider the new IT and AVs (eg. Long range lidars) capabilities. This will create the risk of making the &#x201c;older technology&#x201d; vehicles technologically obsolete and possibly &#x201c;unusable&#x201d;, in the sense of not being able to respond to evolved needs for the service. Today the expected lifetime of an AV does not exceed 6 or 7 years, while a traditional thermic bus or electric trolley has a lifetime of at least 15 years. If the PTOs need to replace their AV fleet every 7 years instead of every 15, this creates a major obstacle for an economically viable deployment.</p>
                <p>The &#x201c;nightmare&#x201d; is thus how to valorise &#x201c;older&#x201d; AVs and extend their useful service lifetime (Preservation of Past Investment). One possible solution, fully compatible with the concept of dynamic, on-demand public transport services, would be to dispatch AVs based on the use case and the required vehicle capabilities. For example, if the older generation vehicle is slower, then it will be dispatched only in areas with low speed limits (like the city center where the speed limits are in general no more than 30 Km/h), or for passengers that require lower speed (eg. are not pressed by the time duration of the trip), or even provide a price differentiation based on the speed of the trip (lower price if you choose a low speed vehicle and in consequence increase your trip time). This type of use-case/capabilities-based vehicle dispatching requires a detailed identification of the target use cases and their correlation to the different vehicle capabilities. The fleet management and orchestration service will need to handle this service provision, while the PTOs will need to identify the policies for the differentiated service levels.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>City HD- maps</title>
                <p>One of the key requirements for the deployment of AVs in a city is the compilation of High Definition (HD) Maps with annotations and information for the smooth and safe operation of the AVs. Each vehicle manufacturer creates its own maps, scanning the deployment roads and making its own annotations. These maps with the inserted annotations are proprietary to each manufacturer.</p>
                <p>From one hand, today the majority of the AV deployments operate in small areas with just a few Kms of routes. As a result, the cost for the creation of the HD maps of the small areas is relatively low, compared to the other costs of deployment, but still quite important. We have seen prices ranging from 5,000 EUR to 25,000 EUR for a Km of road (depending on the associate services).</p>
                <p>On the other hand, today&#x2019;s public transportation buses are deployed in a small percentage of the total roads&#x2019; network of the city. For example, in a city of a population of 500,000 (Geneva, Switzerland) the public transportation road network is 420Km, whereas the total road network of the canton is roughly 1800 Km
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-15">15</xref>
                    </sup>. Passing from fixed line to on-demand, door-to-door, the public transportation road network of the AVs will eventually be required to cover the complete road network of the canton. Considering that many roads will not be able to be served (too narrow, in bad condition, with obstacles (like high speed bumps), private roads etc.) we can safely estimate that from the 1,800Km of road network at least 1,000Km of roads (but the target will be always be to cover the complete network) will need to be served by the automated vehicles. The cost of creating HD maps will thus be very high (in the order of several million EUR).</p>
                <p>The nightmare is that each vehicle manufacturer has today its own standards for HD maps. As a result, the PTO will be forced to either use a single AV manufacturer (resulting in customer lock-in to the vehicle vendor) or pay the mapping of roads twice (or even more times). But the nightmare does not stop there: the city roads are constantly modified, changed, blocked. These changes 
                    <italic toggle="yes">must</italic> be integrated to the HD maps in a very short time (ideally seconds, realistically minutes). Keeping the HD maps up to date will require a continuous re-scanning, analysis and manual annotations of the roads. And if the PTO has opted for multiple vendors, keeping the HD maps of the different vendors synchronized is by itself a major challenge (or nightmare!).</p>
                <p>The challenge is how to keep the HD-maps up to date and how to reuse the HD maps of different vehicle manufactures. Creating a standard for HD-maps and related annotations will require that all the vehicle manufactures join forces and come up with a common open model. How feasible this is, is not yet known, the different manufactures do not really communicate details of their HD maps structure and annotations. Keeping the HD-maps up to date, might be an &#x201c;easier&#x201d; task. Each AV when operated scans the area around it. A comparison of the dynamically scanned area by the AV and static scan, would be able to identify differences and with an intelligent system, create the required HD map updates. Another option is to have a permanent mobile unit visiting &#x201c;incident&#x201d; spots and rescanning and manually updating the HD maps. All these solutions however, have a cost and require fine-tuned methodology and logistics.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Plug and play of AVs in MaaS/ITS systems</title>
                <p>The current model for traditional bus deployment is that the PTO identifies the new bus model/manufacturer (based on some procurement process with clear specifications) and the new vehicles are adapted (by the manufacturer or by the technical services of the PTO) and deployed in the public transportation network.</p>
                <p>On-demand, door-to-door AVs require, among others, to be guided and be connected to the operator fleet management and MaaS/ITS services. However, each AV model has its own interface (API) and its own capabilities. As a result, each AV fleet management provider, provides a custom integration of fleet management services, based on the special capabilities of a specific type of vehicle.</p>
                <p>If the PTO wishes to change to a more performance driven fleet management service, the integration cost and adaptation can be prohibitive (in budget and time to develop and test). Furthermore, the new service provider might not support the PTOs older vehicles and will be required to develop new interfaces, thus increasing the transition costs. The challenge is how the PTO can switch fleet management services and integrate them to its MaaS service with minimal costs (Customer Lock-in to the service provider).</p>
                <p>A solution would be to standardize the AV APIs and protocols, in the same way that web services were standardized, allowing an open model that will be able to adapt and accommodate new capabilities of the future vehicles. This will require collaboration between vehicle manufacturers and the possible creation of a neutral entity that will be the &#x201c;guardian&#x201d; of the open interfaces, operating a similar way as the W3C
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-16">16</xref>
                    </sup>. First steps towards this direction are undertaken by the MaaS Aliance
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-17">17</xref>
                    </sup>, and companies, like the Trapeze group
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-18">18</xref>
                    </sup>, have identified the issue and started working toward this direction.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Critical mass</title>
                <p>A major point in the deployment of large-scale public transport services is the deployment of a critical mass of AVs that will allow real transportation services (and not just a &#x201c;tourist attraction service&#x201d;). Based on past experience
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-14">14</xref>
                    </sup> we have estimated that the minimal critical mass is 15 AVs serving a single site, under a common management service. However, it is clear that not many PTOs have the budget to purchase 15 AVs (in view of their high cost) for a service that has not proven its commercial value. As a result, the demand of AVs is very low, the prices are very high, and this discourages the demand from the PTOs. We somehow need to break this circle and boost the mass development of AVs, bringing the prices down and allowing the deployment of commercially viable services. This is where the support of the European Commission can provide the required funding, by allowing the PTOs to purchase the initial seed-vehicles with Horizon Europe funding, or other financing sources. An increase demand for AVs, will boost the development and investments to AV manufacturers, which will bring down the unit price of a vehicle and further boost the orders for new AVs.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Scaling up the Automated vehicles&#x2019; transport services</title>
                <p>Currently the city public transportation operates on well-defined itineraries and time tables. As mentioned above, in a medium size city like Geneva the public transportation routes with fixed route lines, is about 420Km. Passing to an on-demand door to door service, means covering at least 1000Km of roads. In addition, today, the public transportation in the example of Geneva is served with 472 vehicles (tramways, trolleybus, autobus) and 4 automated vehicles
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-19">19</xref>
                    </sup>. Scaling up to cover the full Geneva area will require 200 to 300 automated vehicles with the parallel decommissioning of 150 to 250 traditional vehicles and keeping the tram and selected trolley lines as backbone. This transition will require long-term planning and a detailed transition plan (assuming that there is an offer from vehicle manufacturers for this very high numbers of vehicles).</p>
                <p>First of all, it must be decided which routes will be served and under which type of services: door-to-door, near-door-to-door, 24/24 vs 18/24 hours of service etc. Once the deployment area is defined the PTO should identify and organize the required city infrastructure: charging points in the area, depot, parking space for vehicles that are on stand-by (chosen to minimize energy consumption - like under shade to minimize the use of air-condition), installation of required V2I technologies for traffic light control, or other needs, ramps for wheel-chair passengers, etc.</p>
                <p>Furthermore, the PTO should create a new IT center for the management of the AVs, and a vehicle maintenance center and of course train the personnel to the new technologies and transport models.</p>
                <p>The choice of the AVs in such high numbers will also be a challenge, depending on the available offers and how to compare the quality of the automated drivers and their adequacy to the local city and weather conditions (narrow roads, frequent rains, vegetation, etc).</p>
                <p>Estimating the costs for the above described scale-up, is not a trivial task and the vast majority of PTOs do not have the required experience to make educated cost estimations. Furthermore, any attempt to reduce costs, might result in service quality degradation and in consequence be rejected by the passengers.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Transport services</title>
                <p>The driver in a public transportation vehicle does not simply drive the vehicle, but offers a number of formal and informal services, from controlling the status of the vehicle, resolving small incidents, providing information to passengers and offering a feeling of safety to the passengers. The suppression of the driver should by no means result to the suppression of these services, which must continue being offered (otherwise we will have a radical quality of service degradation and backlash from the passengers). Today, many solutions are proposed and are implemented, based on live surveillance of the vehicle and its passengers
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-20">20</xref>&#x2013;
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-22">22</xref>
                    </sup>. Systems that are able to identify aggressions in the vehicle, vandalism, as well small malfunctions, are developed and tested. However, this can very fast turn to a regulatory obstacle, since it is based on video surveillance of passengers. Do we store the video for later analysis? Do allow the back-office operator to see the live video and decide of an action to take? In a service like &#x201c;follow my kid&#x201d; where a parent will be able to track the presence a depended person in the bus using face recognition, how we handle the need that we must scan all faces trying to identify one of them?</p>
                <p>The development of driver-replacement in- and out-of-vehicle services, needs a thorough study with active passenger involvement at all stages in order, from one side, the passenger to understand the issues and re-assured on questions of privacy and safety, and from the other side, the PTOs to understand what service need to be introduced and what services can be simply suppressed as not being relevant to the door-to-door, on-demand public transport operation.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Transport policies</title>
                <p>Assuming that the above logistics, technology and infrastructure issues have been resolved, the PTO will face a new challenge, due to the radical paradigm change: from fixed line operation to on-demand, door-to-door driverless operation. New transport policies need to be designed, that will be socially acceptable and support the economic viability of the transport services. Some examples of the required transport policies that need to be defined include: a) what is the minimal distance for which a passenger can order a trip? Do we allow trips of just 50m? (considering that ordering a vehicle, might force it to divert its route by 200m to serve a 50m trip, which is highly expensive and might end up degrading the service quality). b) Do we differentiate trip price based on trip distance, speed of delivery, waiting time etc. (going away from today&#x2019;s flat rate models)? c) What should we do for no-shows? Do we allow the passenger to order a trip and not use it? Do charge the trip at all cases? Are there penalties for regular &#x201c;no-show&#x201d;s? d) how long should the vehicle wait the passenger? 1 minute, 5 minutes? Knowing that any delay will affect the overall service quality and increase the overall cost, what can be the policy of the PTO? e) how do we make exceptions for elderly, people with special needs etc? Do we required them to formally prove their special need? Do we ask a pregnant woman to prove she is pregnant? And what about privacy considerations? f) Do we provide for special services, like if a passenger wants to be alone in the vehicle? this can be the case for night service when we transport vulnerable passengers. Or this is not considered as &#x201c;public transportation&#x201d; and we create special services using the chartered vehicle services? g) how do we handle false reservations? For example, a passenger reserves for one person, but enters with two large suitcases, taking up all the space in the vehicle, h) how we react to incidents (from small vehicle malfunctions, to passenger related incidents)? We need to have intervention teams roaming the city, but what are the delays to intervene? How we distinguish for different types of incidents the urgency to intervene? i) what we do in case of incidents in the vehicle, like vandalism, aggression etc? do we stop the vehicle and send an intervention team? Do we store the video and refer to the authorities?</p>
                <p>The PTO will need to define new policies, in coordination with passenger associations and of course state authorities, and these policies should be integrated in the fleet management services and supported with specialized technology, like an incident service dashboard. Some of the incidents (but which?) should be treated automatically, with predefined actions, while others will require human intervention. Furthermore, the modification of policies and corresponding actions should be very simple to introduce, so that the back-office operator can change them dynamically, according to instructions and the current overall situation, adapting thresholds and automated actions.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Idle vehicles during off-peak hours</title>
                <p>One of the advantages of using automated vehicles in public transportation, is that the vehicle is operating only when there is a need. This means that during off-peak hours an important number of vehicles will be sitting idle in a parking spot waiting for the demand to go up. This saves energy, from one hand, but has high cost (we cannot have vehicles that are used just 30% per day (7 out of 24 hours)). We thus need to find ways to reuse the vehicles. This can be done by making the vehicles available for non-public transport usage. Since the vehicles have all the authorization to operate in the city streets, we can use them for services like urban logistics or private transport. This can be done by creating a platform implementing 
                    <italic toggle="yes">Vehicle as a Service</italic> model, where the excess capacity of the AV fleet becomes available to be used by other service providers (like LaaS). In other words, implement a &#x201c;chartering&#x201d; model for AVs. The control of a vehicle will be passed to another urban transport provider (Logistics or person), under well defined Service Level Agreements (SLAs). This way we can have virtual operators, using the excess capacity and offering non-public transportation services. This can become an important revenue source for the PTOs, allowing them to better valorize their vehicles.</p>
                <p>However, several key questions need to answered. First of all how to define the SLAs and how to implement and enforce them? Second, what will happen if during the chartered operation the vehicle is damaged or was dirtied and cannot be used at the end of the chartering time? And finally, what will be the impact to the overall public transportation service quality?</p>
            </sec>
        </sec>
        <sec>
            <title>Making a dream come true</title>
            <p>Today, as we have seen from past projects and initiatives, we are in the crossroad for the deployment of AVs in public transportation. Many PTOs have experimented with AVs for short or long periods, identifying the possible advantages in adopting the technology, but can not afford to continue small demonstrator deployments. For these reasons we see PTOs simply terminating the experiments and deciding to wait and see, without making any plans to integrate AVs in their service offer. On the other side the vehicle manufactures need to increase the number of AVs deployed in order to be able to work and improve the shortcomings identified in the experimental deployments. The net result is that the lack of a market does not allow manufacturers to invest to vehicle improvements and the lack of improved vehicles does not allow the PTOs to plan large scale deployments. The evolution is thus very slow. This is where, in Europe, the support of European commission can play a major role, by providing the seed money required. In this direction the European Commission is funding a large number of projects under the Horizon 2020 and Horizon Europe frameworks.</p>
            <p>We are participating in two flagship projects, AVENUE and ULTIMO, in which we took a different path than other projects, and allocated large parts of the budget to the PTOs for the purchase AVs, opening the way for a sustainable deployment.</p>
            <p>In the rest of this section we give a presentation of the two projects, presenting the achievements of the AVENUE project and the targets of the ULTIMO project.</p>
            <sec>
                <title>The H2020 AVENUE project</title>
                <p>One of the major and successful deployments of on-demand, door-to-door public transportation was achieved within the Horizon 2020 project AVENUE
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-23">23</xref>
                    </sup>. AVENUE, was a four and a half years H2020 project financed by the European Commission. The project started in May 2018 and was completed in October 2022. With 22 partners and a 15.5MEUR funding, the project has designed and carried out full-scale demonstrations of urban public transport services with fully automated vehicles, in 6 European demonstrator cities (Geneva, Lyon, Copenhagen, Luxembourg, Sion, Esch-sur-Alzette). The project deployed, for the first time worldwide, small fleets of automated minibuses in low to medium demand areas offering fully automated on-demand, door-to-door, shared public transportation services. The AVENUE vision for future public transport in urban and suburban areas was that automated vehicles will ensure safe, rapid, economic, sustainable and personalised transport of passengers. AVENUE introduced disruptive public transportation paradigms on the basis of on-demand, door-to-door services, setting up a new model of public transportation, by revisiting the offered public transportation services, and suppressing prescheduled fixed bus itineraries.</p>
                <p>At the end of the AVENUE project, our mission was achieved, having demonstrated that automated vehicles have the potential to become the future solution for public transportation, and having provided recommendations and guidelines for the different actors towards the deployment of large-scale AVs in public transportation. The AVENUE project has demonstrated the economic, environmental and social potential of automated vehicles for both public transport operators and passengers, and we were able to identify the needs for a successful service deployment of automated vehicles in public transportation
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-23">23</xref>
                    </sup>.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>Overview of the AVENUE project results</title>
                <p>The Automated vehicles employed in the AVENUE project, fully and automatically manage the navigation and road behaviour in an open street environment. The vehicles are capable to recognise obstacles (and identify some of them), identify moving and stationary objects, and automatically decide to bypass them or wait behind them, based on the defined policies. For example, with small changes in its route the AVENUE mini-bus is able to bypass a parked car, while it will slow down and follow behind a slowly moving car. The AVENUE mini-buses are able to handle different complex road situations, like entering and exiting round-about in the presence of other fast running cars, stop in zebra crossings, communicate with infrastructure via V2I interfaces (ex. red light control).</p>
                <p>In the AVENUE project we were operating SAE Level 4 vehicles (NAVYA Autonom Shuttle
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-24">24</xref>
                    </sup>), with a capacity of 14 persons, and authorized to operate at a maximum speed of 25-30 km/h, depending on the local regulatory framework. In the current deployments the speed does not exceed 23 Km/h, with an average operational speed of 14 to 20 Km/h. Another, more important reason for limiting the vehicle speed is safety for passengers and pedestrians. Due to the fact that the LIDAR used in the AVENUE vehicles has a range of 100m and the usable range for obstacle identification is no more than 40 meters
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-25">25</xref>
                    </sup>, and considering that the vehicle must safely stop in case of an obstacle on the road (which will be &#x201c;seen&#x201d; within the 40 meters distance) we cannot guarantee a safe braking if the speed is more than 25 Km/h. Note that technically the vehicle can make a harsh break and stop within 40 meters in high speeds (40&#x2013;50 Km/h) but then the breaking would be too harsh putting in risk the passengers. The partners in the project are working in finding an optimal point between passenger and pedestrian safety.</p>
                <p>Due to legal requirements a Safety Operator must always be present in the vehicle, able to take control any moment, although at the deployments we have reached a 99% automated operation. Additionally, at the control room, a Supervisor is present controlling the fleet operations. An Intervention Team is present in the deployment area ready to intervene in case of incident to any of the mini-busses.  </p>
                <p>A series of passenger services were introduced and validated in the project
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-26">26</xref>
                    </sup>. With the use of an on-board computer and on-board cameras and microphones, we developed and tested several safety services. The system installed was able to locally identify aggressions, vandalism, forgotten objects, number of passengers, available space, and send an incident notification to the back-office operator for further action.</p>
                <p>In addition with the collection of real data from long term deployments and by incorporating known data from traditional public transportation service, we were able to develop an economic analysis tool
                    <sup>
                        <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-27">27</xref>
                    </sup>, that allowed us to estimate the costs for the deployment of a public transportation service, given the different options (from site size, quality of service level (waiting delays, transport delays), number of vehicles, costs of vehicles etc).</p>
                <p>A major result of the AVENUE project was that we were able to clearly identify the gap from technology deployment to service deployment. This knowledge was used to define the next step, to be implemented under the ULTIMO Horizon Europe project.</p>
            </sec>
            <sec>
                <title>The road ahead - the Horizon Europe ULTIMO project</title>
                <p>Based on the experience gained in the AVENUE project a more ambitious project was launched in the Horizon Europe Framework, the ULTIMO project. A 4 years project (October 2022 to September 2026), with 23 partners and a total financial contribution of 40 MEUR (24MEUR from the European Commission and 16 MEUR from the Swiss Federal Government) targeting to create and deploy in three sites in Europe the very first viable, economically feasible and sustainable integration of Automated Vehicles in user-centric Public Transportation services, with integrated LaaS urban goods transportation. The ULTIMO project aims in resolving all the issues presented above, making the dream come closer to reality.</p>
                <p>Within ULTIMO we will deploy multi-vendor SAE L4 AVs into large scale sites (3 sites, each with 15 or more multi-vendor AVs per site), designing a user-centric, on-demand, door-to-door, shared, economically viable public transportation and logistics services. Our target is to operate the very first large public transportation service without safety operator on-board, in fully automated, mission management mode and with the support of innovative user centric passenger services. All aspects for improving the services for citizen to offer a real alternative to privately owned cars will be addressed. A further focus will be to enable viable economic deployments, ranging from valorization of past investments (older vehicles), development of economically sustainable passenger and transport services without safety driver, and introducing the concept of vehicle chartering for vehicle reuse in LaaS services.</p>
                <p>In the ULTIMO project we will develop and integrate standardised APIs for vehicles and fleet management services, validate the dynamic change of fleet management service provider, integrate multi-vendor vehicles in a plug and play model, and most of all, design passenger services in direct collaboration with the service users.</p>
            </sec>
        </sec>
        <sec sec-type="conclusions">
            <title>Conclusion</title>
            <p>Automated Vehicles for public transportation have been identified as a very promising solution to the ever-increasing urban mobility problems. However, in spite of the huge investments in technology improvement, the passage from &#x201c;technology offer&#x201d; to &#x201c;service offer&#x201d; is not yet well understood and we have yet to see a real commercial deployment of AVs in urban mobility. The reason for this is total lack of viable and sustainable business models, which in turn is the result of the lack of experience in the creation of a new mobility paradigm, moving away from the traditional fixed route and time-table services.</p>
            <p>The deployment of a full service of public transportation with automated mini-busses in a city will require more than just a few vehicles operating in a certain area. Going from fixed route, fixed time-tables to on-demand, door-to-door, driverless, highly dynamic public transport, will require a multi-target approach in order to come up to a viable, user-oriented, economically sustainable service. In this paper we presented the key elements that need to be studied and where solution must be developed. From one side a long term planning needs to be put in place by the PTOs and PTAs, in a depth of decade, and new policies, infrastructures, passengers services need to be conceived and implemented. From the other side new open standards supporting interoperability of automated related technologies must be developed and adopted, opening the market for a real competition between the technology actors (be it vehicle manufactures, fleet management and orchestration providers, V2X technology developers etc) can be established, creating a sustainable ecosystem.</p>
            <p>The issues presented in this paper, although being the most important, are not the only ones. Other challenges include the re-education of maintenance personnel from mechanical to IT and electronics, as well as the phasing out of the existing drivers or their conversion to new functions (like intervention teams, back-office operators). Furthermore, any plan to deploy automated vehicles with on-demand, door-to-door public transportation service, might generate a backlash from other public transportation actors, like taxis, that will see this service as a direct threat to their business. Another major challenge that needs also to be resolved, is the certification of the automated drivers. Today, public transportation vehicles are certified for their mechanical capabilities, and the human driver is &#x201c;certified&#x201d; for his/her driving capabilities. Certifying the automated vehicle driving capabilities, is today an open question. How to approach these issues, and others that can only be identified once a real service is deployed, will require a concentrated effort from PTOs, PTAs, legislators and service users to come up with viable solutions.</p>
            <p>This is eventually the target of the European project ULTIMO
                <sup>
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-28">28</xref>
                </sup>, started in October 2022, to set the basis of a large-scale deployment and develop the required standards, policies and roadmaps for the creation of viable, user-oriented and economically sustainable public transportation service with automated vehicles. In the ULTIMO project we expect to have the complete service operating with 15 vehicles per site in the last year of the project, that is in 2026 and thus be able to identify yet unknown issues in this new public transport paradigm.</p>
        </sec>
