            <p>This is a very interesting topical paper that deals with a problem that we will soon have upon us; how public transport can become AV-based without any significant problems. In that sense there is a degree of the paper being genuinely pro-active. At the same time some issues may not happen with the way things are predicted herein. Now, let's go to my criticism and points to look at and hopefully address:</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 1. ULTIMO is not mentioned in the plain language summary - you need to have this squeezed in.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 2. I could not read the Table (too small) - this must be problematic to readers.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 3. The usage of academic referencing can be hugely enhanced. There are so many interesting and fitting papers that you could have used to back up some points of your work. Referencing is an avenue for validation and legitimacy. You need to upgrade your engagement with the AV-related literature.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 4. Define MaaS and other interventions/terms you introduce. Make things easier for your readers.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 5. You need to use forgiving language when you bring on the challenges. These can be eight but maybe actually are more than that (or even less). Some cannot be foreseen now. Be more tentative and let the reader now that this your prediction and it is a guesstimate.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 6. I need to see a more explicit linkage of how your projects (AVENUE &amp; ULTIMO) tackle these eight challenges. Are both for all eight challenges? Make the links more visible with each of the challenges you are describing.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 7. The AVENUE results refer rather to a project description; this is not the same. What is your contribution per se? How did you explore the eight challenges? What are your main study results per se?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 8. The title can be more suitable to your context. Why for instance the use of the word 'hidden'?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 9. I do have reservations about societal impacts like the dismissal of thousands of drivers and possibly environmental impacts with the increase in vehicle miles travelled. You write from a very optimistic standpoint until the very end. Maybe you need to be more cautious with some characterisations.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> All in all though this is a really intriguing read.</p>
            <p>Where applicable, are recommendations and next steps explained clearly for others to follow? (Please consider whether others in the research community would be able to implement guidelines or recommendations and/or constructively engage in the debate)</p>
