            <p>This letter analyzes the key issues identified from a field project (called AVENUE) deploying AVs as a part of public transport in multiple cities and illustrates the follow-up project called ULTIMO. The projects seem important as the autonomous vehicles had been evaluated mostly in the simulation environment particularly for the large-scale operating scenarios without the knowledge of actual performance in a real-world setting.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Regarding the article, I suggest the following comments, which I believe will help the authors to improve the overall quality: 
                <list list-type="order">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>I think the paper needs to be structured as: (1) project explanation (AVENUE needs to be summarized before specifying the challenges); (2) presenting the findings from the field test (which is not explicitly explained or quantitatively presented); (3) discussion on the challenges/issues (based on the field observations in the previous step); (4) conclusion with suggestions or future direction (in the upcoming project ULTIMO) to address the issues (identified from AVENUE).</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Regarding the presentation of AVENUE, it is suggested to provide (1) the service configuration (i.e. fleet sizes, operating details &#x2013; start/end times, locations of parking/charging, etc) in each city and (2) the performance of AV service (from the perspectives of user, fleet operator, infrastructure, and vehicle related measures, etc).</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Then the authors can support the argument on the eight issues in a clear manner by addressing the followings:</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list> 
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Implications on operations and planning for different types of cities</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Effects of the integration of passenger and freight (LaaS) on the fleet utilization</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Possible congestion by the &#x2018;slow&#x2019; Avs (having speed limit of 20~30km/h)</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>User experience on wait/travel times after introducing AV minibus</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list> Some minors are: 
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Not sure if this is the format of this journal, but please consider to label each section.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>I would choose the word carefully: e.g. &#x201c;vision&#x201d; instead of &#x201c;dream&#x201d;, &#x201c;a worst scenario (or aspect)&#x201d; instead of &#x201c;nightmare&#x201d;.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Please use consistent terms over the manuscript and avoid unnecessary duplication of sentence (or description). The authors may have a clear definition of the terms at the beginning, e.g. 'on-demand door-to-door public transport service (automated demand-responsive transit -&gt; ADRT)'.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>&#x201c;The fleet of 335 minibuses&#x201d; seems correct (15+160+160) instead of &#x201c;340&#x201d; in page 6.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>&#x201c;the change from human-driven buses to automated mini-buses&#x201d; instead of &#x201c;The change from driver busses to automated mini-buses&#x201d; in page 6.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Not sure but please check if &#x201c;3,000km&#x201d; correct instead of &#x201c;3.000 KM&#x201d; in page 6.</p>
