            <p>In this Open Letter, the authors present an analysis of eight challenges pertaining to the deployment of automated public transportation systems in cities. Specifically, they address the issues of scalability and commercial viability. The authors demonstrate how insights into potentially resolving these issues were gained from a recently completed project and also how further investigations would be made through a future pilot project.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Comments 
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>My impression is that the paper tries to accomplish two objectives: the first being the issues surrounding the implementation of automated mobility for public transit and the second being a summary of the findings from the AVENUE project (pilot in 6 European cities).</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list> While the paper begins with a broad treatment of the issues, it does not appear to provide a general resolution, and the paper then ends with ULTIMO as the next step. But will ULTIMO alone solve or address all the issues pertaining to automated mobility in transit? Are there other similar pilots or projects in the pipeline elsewhere that the authors could highlight?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The authors could address this by revising the final paragraph of the conclusion or by revising the title to indicate that the focus is on lessons from specific previous/future pilot projects/experiments. The Introduction, however, does a good job of motivating the AVENUE project. 
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The organization of the paper could be improved. Between pages 1 and 8, the authors highlight the fact that the 8 issues/challenges were identified through their work on the AVENUE project. However, the AVENUE project is not described in detail until after the challenges section. Perhaps the AVENUE project could be described first, then the 8 challenges, and then ULTIMO presented in the "Making a dream come true" section. On page 11, the authors write "we are participating in two flagship projects..." But later on, they mention that AVENUE ended in October 2022. So, it should be clarified that AVENUE is completed, which means that they "participated" in AVENUE and will participate or are already participating in "ULTIMO."</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Related to point (2) above: The results from AVENUE could be more clearly described. Could the authors provide a table with more quantitative information/results, such as size of pilot (number of vehicles), number of passengers served, city characteristics, summary of quantitative outcomes, and so on? These would make the letter stronger, especially since much of the discussion of challenges was hinged on the AVENUE experience.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>I am a bit concerned with the characterization of the challenges as "hidden" in the title. Yes, the authors are investigating, enumerating, detailing, or analysing challenges relating to deployment. But not all are hidden or latent. Several are obvious and well-known, as the authors mention. I would suggest revising the title accordingly. E.g. "analyzing the challenges," or "investigating the challenges," among other options.</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>The manuscript needs to be revised for punctuation, grammatical correctness and appropriate idiomatic usage. There are too many to exhaustively list, but I will give a few:</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list> - p5: "powerful" instead of "powerfully"</p>
